> 
> Yo guys, anyone been playing NH with any of the rescale mods (2, 3.7, 6.4)? 
> I'm debating my setup for 1.1 and 64-bit, but not sure if it'll be just plain too hard if the system is any bigger...

> 
> Eddiew, I was just going to ask exactly the same question!

I play with Kscale2 and NH (and FAR), and I'm finding it quite fun. I haven't changed any parts, but I do use procedural parts and modular fuel tanks to make design a bit easier, and Stage Recovery for funds. I eventually settled on a career funds multiplier of 0.7 and science multiplier of 0.8 (with DMagic science), and I'm finding it challenging to make money and get new parts, but not impossible. As far as progression, I am about to land on the Mun, and I've already made an Aptur landing, but that's as far as I've gotten so take it how you will.

(Also, I wrote an MM patch to increase the terrain deformity of the planets to keep everything from getting flattened. It only affects the Kopernicus planets though, not the stock ones. You do end up with some monstrously high peaks on some of the planets, so watch your orbit altitude. ![;)](//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_wink.gif)

The second half of the patch removes the SpaceCenter section from the Kerbin config, which fixes the issue that Kopernicus has with rescaled Kerbin and incorrrect recovery distances. It does mean the runway hangs out into the ocean a tad, though.)

> 
> 
> 
> {  
>  @Body[\*],\*  
>  {  
>  @PQS  
>  {  
>  @Mods  
>  {  
>  @VertexHeightMap,\*  
>  {  
>  @deformity \*= 2  
>  }  
>  @VertexSimplexHeight,\*  
>  {  
>  @deformity \*= 2  
>  }  
>  @VertexSimplexHeightAbsolute,\*  
>  {  
>  @deformity \*= 2  
>  }  
>  @VertexHeightNoise,\*  
>  {  
>  @deformity \*= 2  
>  }  
>  @VertexHeightNoiseVertHeightCurve2,\* //3  
>  {  
>  @deformity \*= 2  
>  }  
>  @VertexHeightNoiseVertHeight,\*  
>  {  
>  @deformity \*= 2  
>  }  
>  @VertexVoronoi,\*  
>  {  
>  @deformity \*= 2  
>  }  
>  }  
>  }  
>  }  
> }  
>   
> //Remove Spacecenter so recovery distance is right  
> @Kopernicus:AFTER[Wercho]   
> {  
>  @Body[Kerbin]  
>  {  
>  !SpaceCenter{}  
>  }  
> }
> 
> 
>     @Kopernicus:AFTER[Wercho] //double the deformity 
